description:
Myuchelys georgesi, also known as the Georges' turtle, is a species of freshwater turtle endemic to eastern Australia. It belongs to the family Chelidae, which includes a diverse group of side-necked turtles found primarily in South America and Australia.

The Georges' turtle is a medium-sized turtle, with a carapace (upper shell) length typically ranging from 20 to 30 centimeters. Its carapace is oval-shaped and can vary in color from dark brown to olive-green, often with yellow or orange markings. The plastron (lower shell) is yellowish or cream-colored.

This species is found in slow-moving rivers, streams, and wetlands within the coastal regions of eastern Australia, primarily in the states of New South Wales and Queensland. It is an omnivorous species, feeding on a variety of aquatic plants, insects, crustaceans, and small vertebrates.

Myuchelys georgesi is considered a threatened species, with its populations declining due to factors such as habitat loss, predation, and collection for the pet trade. Conservation efforts, including habitat protection and captive breeding programs, are ongoing to ensure the long-term survival of this unique Australian turtle species.
